d redundancies and industrial closures. Some of their responses included strikes, factory occupations, the organisation and politicisation of the unemployed, consent to radical left-wing municipal politics, as well as tacit endorsement a period of violent civil unrest. This critique concludes that in the range, intensity and use of innovative tactics deployed during these conflicts, Liverpool was distinctive.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aStrikes and lockoutszEnglandzLiverpoolxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorking classzEnglandzLiverpoolxHistoryy20th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh  aLiverpool.  aNeoliberalism.  aResistance.  aSocialism.  aThatcherism.  ade-industrialisation.  amonetarism.  aunemployment.  aworking-class.1 aMarren, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packagez978311128282440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781784997052423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781784997052/original  a978-3-11-128282-4  Manchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packageb2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles